    <text type="letter">
        <body>
            <pb xml:id="leaf001r" facs="loc.03635.001_large.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <opener>
                <dateline>
                    <name type="place">Boston,</name>
                    <date notBefore="1888-12-06" notAfter="1891-12-06">6th December</date>
                </dateline>
                <salute>Walt. Whitman</salute>
                <salute>Dear Sir&#8211;</salute>
            </opener>
            <p>I have read with pleasure, your "Leaves of Grass," and admire their impudence and
                beauty,&#8212;but can't say which I admire most. I have lent my copy to others. Some
                are in ecstasies over it, while others think no man should be allowed to print,
                write, buy, sell or read <hi rend="underline">so</hi> wicked a book.</p>
            <p>Now you may call me a fool for my request, but if you will comply with it, I shall be
                just as well satisfied. I want your <hi rend="underline">autograph</hi> attached to
                an extract from your leaves, <pb xml:id="leaf001v" facs="loc.03635.002_large.jpg"
                    type="verso"/> or, to a fresh Leaf. I wish to frame it, to hang in my room, in
                company with a autograph of Charles Mackay,<ptr target="loc.03635_n2"/> another of
                my favorites. Please write me on a half-sheet of note paper,&#8212;this
                size&#8212;&#38;return according to the endorsed envelope.</p>
            <closer>
                <salute rend="right">Truly yours,</salute>
                <signed><hi rend="underline">Wm Robinson</hi></signed>
                <note type="editorial" place="bottom-right" resp="#ww">Wm Robinson (ask'g
                    autograph)</note>
            </closer>
        </body>
    </text>
